+# SDPO: Self-Distillation Preference Optimization
+
+SDPO (Self-Distillation Preference Optimization) is a reinforcement learning approach where one model serves as both the teacher and student, eliminating the need for a separate reference model.
+
+## Overview
+
+SDPO extends the Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) approach by using the model itself as the reference policy. This enables self-distillation where the model learns to improve upon its own previous state.
+
+### Key Features
+
+- **Single Model Architecture**: No need for a separate reference model
+- **Self-Distillation**: The model learns to improve upon its own previous state
+- **Memory Efficient**: Reduces memory requirements by eliminating the need for a reference model
+- **Compatible with DPO Loss Types**: Supports all DPO loss types (sigmoid, hinge, ipo, etc.)
+
+## Installation
+
+```bash
+pip install trl
+```
+
+## Usage
+
+### Basic Usage
+
+```python
+from datasets import load_dataset
+from trl.experimental.sdpo import SDPOConfig, SDPOTrainer
+
+# Load a preference dataset
+dataset = load_dataset("trl-lib/ultrafeedback_binarized", split="train")
+
+# Initialize the SDPO trainer
+trainer = SDPOTrainer(
+    model="Qwen/Qwen2.5-0.5B-Instruct",
+    train_dataset=dataset,
+    args=SDPOConfig(
+        output_dir="./sdpo_results",
+        beta=0.1,  # Controls the "temperature" of the policy update
+        learning_rate=5e-6,
+        per_device_train_batch_size=4,
+        num_train_epochs=1,
+    ),
+)
+
+# Train the model
+trainer.train()
+
+# Save the trained model
+trainer.save_model("./sdpo_results")
+```
+
+## When to Use SDPO
+
+- **Memory Constraints**: When you have limited GPU memory
+- **Small Models**: Ideal for training smaller models where memory is a concern
+- **Experimental Work**: When you want to try self-distillation approaches
+- **Single Model Training**: When you prefer not to maintain a separate reference model
